he world. I skip on most randoms, and usually give away items I don't need, never selling anything. All my eq was given to me from friends and my great guild buddies. <br>
<br>
I think I approach EQ the same way I approach other games like Baldur's Gate and Diablo. From an RP perspective. I think this is the way VI wants us to approach it. Not to kill Zordakalicus Ragefire because you wanna get an item, but because he is the villian and all of us are the heros. Heros don't argue about looting rights because all they cared about was eliminating the evil. I can rest easy knowing that that dispicable dragon only sees the light of day for a couple minutes before he is sent back into the void. A Magic Flail? The Breastplate of Donal? Mere trinkets that mask the greater good. I know this is a hard concept for everyone to understand and that EQ will never be like this for anyone, so let the debating continue...<br>
<br>
...I agree with Velondra. In my entire EQ career from May 1999 to today I have followed these two rules when approaching a group of players fighting mobs in one spot. I remember getting into arguements on the chessboard in Butcherblock, HHP and HHK, forced to move onto more difficult areas to hunt, since gimps wouldn't hunt there. I also have been waiting months and will continue to wait months for the Water Sprinkler. Although I have not put in my time, nor will I ever. I agree with Draelyn in that it is pure INSANITY for someone to camp 6 days straight to get this item. Although I admire your vigilance, I gotta ask myself what is this game coming to? <br>
<br>
